Title: Thinking in Systems: A Primer
Author: Donella H. Meadows
My Review:
Nice introduction to systems thinking.

Warning: after reading this book you'll start noticing feedback loops all around you.

It touches on system thinking fundamentals like stocks, flows & feedback loops.
I love how it provides real-life examples (fish population, economic failure modes,...) and offers pointers on how to intervene in failing systems.
I read this work through the eyes of a consultant/software developer and a lot of the advice offered translates directly to my day job. Highly recommended!

Title: Badass: Making Users Awesome
Author: Kathy Sierra
My Review:
Wow. Whether you build apps/websites, write content for your company website, customer support or are involved in writing user manuals, this book is full of insights on how to improve on that. Also, if you coach/teach people new skills that require expertise (photography, software development, musical instrument,...) you will take away lots of new insights from this one. It's a fun and fast read with lots of visual aids.

The main message: don't focus on "brand engagement" strategies, instead help your user get better at whatever context the tools/services you provide are embedded in. The rest will follow automagically. How do you help your users get better? By helping them in whatever way you can in becoming badass of course! Think: deliberate practice, minimizing cognitive resource leaks, providing a path to mastery,...

Definitely check this out if you like any of:

Title: Practical Object Oriented Design in Ruby
Author: Sandi Metz
My Review:
This book is one of the few that really helps developers understand the intricacies of "real OO". Not just the usual "procedural programming in an OO language", but the real stuff. Focus on messages not objects, keep things small and focused, how to achieve loose coupling, all the good stuff. It doesn't slam you with acronyms and jargon, it explains the most fundamental principles in clear terms & with concrete examples.

The only reason I'm not giving this 5 stars is because I have some issues with the last chapter regarding testing. I mostly work in statically typed languages and some of the really important messages in that chapter get muddled with some extra tests that are only required in dynamic languages due to their lack of interfaces as first-class concept. The real important stuff of that chapter is one of the few and concrete explanations of testing in isolation & contract testing as popularized by J.B. Rainsberger. Sadly, this message gets muddled with less than relevant details of testing whether objects adhere to an implicit interface/duck type.

With that caveat in mind, highly recommended!

Title: Implementing Domain-Driven Design
Author: Vaughn Vernon
My Review:
A really good refresher on the DDD essentials. A bit verbose at times, but contains lots of interesting nuggets.

It places proper emphasis on non-technical aspects like Ubiquitous language and Bounded Contexts.

I also really enjoy the more technical aspects (e.g. like "How large are your Aggregates?", "How to handle Value Objects with an ORM?"). These technical details are very Java-focused but the concepts translate nicely to other mainstream languages.

Not the first book I'd recommend readers new to DDD but definitely worth the read if you are working in a project using (or want to start) DDD!
